hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the rectangle $R = [0, \pi] \times [0, 4]$ in the Cartesian plane. A function $f: R \to \mathbb{R}$ is defined such that it is non-zero only on the line segment described by the equation $y = \frac{4}{\pi}x$ for $x \in [0, \pi]$. On this line segment, the function's value is given by $f(x, y) = 1 + \cos(x)$. Everywhere else on the rectangle $R$, the function's value is $0$.

Explicitly, the function is defined as:
$$
f(x, y) = \begin{cases}
1 + \cos(x)  \text{if } y = \frac{4}{\pi}x \text{ and } 0 \le x \le \pi \\
0  \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

The double integral of $f$ over $R$, denoted as $\iint_R f(x,y) \,dA$, is defined as the unique value $I$ that satisfies $L(f, P) \le I \le U(f, P)$ for all possible partitions $P$ of the rectangle $R$, provided that the function is Riemann integrable. Here, $L(f, P)$ and $U(f, P)$ are the lower and upper Riemann sums for the partition $P$, respectively.

By constructing a suitable sequence of partitions and analyzing the behavior of the corresponding upper and lower Riemann sums, determine the exact value of the double integral $\iint_R f(x,y) \,dA$.
